[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    463[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Step 5 docstring's swap-in code for [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mxgboost.Booster.predict()[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m is the right teaching move: it makes the placeholder/learned-ranker boundary explicit, and the reader can see exactly what would change. This is more useful than vague "in production, train a real model" prose.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    464[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m_get_opensearch_client[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m is module-level cached on first call (the lazy initializer), which directly addresses the warm-Lambda latency concern flagged in the Recipe 4.2 review. The comment explains why: [38;2;180;142;173m*[38;2;180;142;173m"In a Lambda warm container, the SigV4 credential resolution and TLS handshake happen once per process rather than once per invocation."[38;2;180;142;173m*[K
